# CadQuery Project Conventions

## Repository Layout

- Keep reusable model definitions in root `*.py` model files.
- Keep generic CLI utilities in `scripts/` (export/check helpers).
- Write generated outputs only to `exports/` (do not write exports to project root).
- Do not add model-specific scripts under `scripts/`; scripts must work from passed parameters.

## Model Interface Contract

- Every model module must define:
  - `PARAMS` (dict of default dimensions/options)
  - `MODEL_NAME` (stable model identifier string)
  - `build_model(p=PARAMS)` returning a dict with:
    - `name`: model name
    - `assembly`: CadQuery assembly (or `None`)
    - `parts`: non-empty dict mapping `part_name -> cadquery shape`
- Keep part naming stable (`body`, `base`, `lid`, `rear_cover`, etc.) to avoid downstream script breakage.
- Avoid script-specific assumptions inside model modules; scripts consume only the standard `build_model()` output.

## Modeling Rules

- Any printable part (`body`, `base`, `lid`) must be a single solid.
- Prefer overlapping geometry (not only touching faces) when uniting parts.
- For structural joins, add explicit bridges/ribs so boolean unions remain connected.
- Keep key dimensions in `PARAMS` and avoid hard-coded magic numbers in assembly placement.

## Validation Workflow

- After substantial geometry edits, always run:
  - `./.venv311/bin/python scripts/check_connectivity.py --model <python_module_name>`
- Before commits that touch model geometry or export logic, rerun:
  - `./.venv311/bin/python scripts/check_connectivity.py --model <python_module_name>`
- If multiple models are affected, run the check once per affected model.
- Only treat a model as valid when both conditions hold:
  - `solids == 1` for each printable part
  - `isValid == True`
- If the check fails, fix connectivity first; do not export or commit as final.
- This requirement applies to every printable output file in this repo (existing and new models): every part must satisfy `solids == 1` and `isValid == True`.

## Export Workflow

- Use script entrypoints, not ad-hoc exporter commands:
  - `./.venv311/bin/python scripts/export_model.py --model <python_module_name>`
- Always run connectivity checks before export; never treat multi-solid output as acceptable.
- Keep export paths configurable via `--out` and default to `exports/`.
- Prefer script-level generic export logic driven by `build_model()` output; avoid per-model branching in scripts.

## Script CLI Consistency

- Keep `scripts/check_connectivity.py` and `scripts/export_model.py` parameter conventions aligned:
  - `--model <python_module_name>` identifies the model module to import.
  - `--params <json_path>` applies validated PARAMS overrides.
- `check_connectivity.py` must not write CAD files; it is validation-only.
- `export_model.py` must write outputs only to the configured `--out` directory (default `exports/`).
- When adding new shared CLI behaviors, apply them to both scripts when meaningful and document them in `README.md`.

## Git Hygiene

- Never commit virtual environments or generated CAD outputs.
- Keep `.gitignore` aligned with `.venv*`, `__pycache__`, and `exports/`.
